BOOT-SEQUENCE long-gap lesson (iter-22, 2026-06-21): a /loop re-fire after a multi-minute inter-fire gap that runs its boot sequence (cat .status.json, bun x gm-plugkit upgrade, sleep-waits, Skill re-entry) ENTIRELY in Bash/Skill tool calls does NOT reset the rs-plugkit long-gap instruction clock -- so the FIRST spool verb after boot (here git_fetch at gap_ms=333443) trips deviation.long-gap-no-instruction, and the inter-fire idle trips deviation.mid-chain-stall. Both are gate-positive + self-recover (dispatch instruction, re-dispatch the denied verb), but they are avoidable: on a /loop re-fire, dispatch `instruction` as the FIRST spool verb immediately after the boot probe confirms a live watcher, BEFORE any git_fetch/git_status/codesearch, to reset the clock. The platform Bash/Read/Skill calls are invisible to the gate (it only sees spool verbs), so a long Bash-only boot looks identical to an idle stall. Not a code defect; a boot-ordering behavioral fix. Witnessed: gmsniff own:2 this fire, both these exact classes, both recovered.